  "prompt": "How much sugar is good for health?",
  "response": "The amount of sugar that is considered \"good\" for health can vary depending on individual health needs, age, and activity levels. However, health organizations provide general guidelines for added sugars:\n\n1. **American Heart Association (AHA)**: Recommends that women limit added sugars to no more than 6 teaspoons (25 grams) per day, and men limit added sugars to no more than 9 teaspoons (37.5 grams) per day.\n\n2. **World Health Organization (WHO)**: Advises that added sugars should make up less than 10% of total daily energy intake. A further reduction to below 5% (approximately 25 grams or 6 teaspoons) is suggested for additional health benefits.\n\n3. **Dietary Guidelines for Americans**: Recommend that added sugars should comprise less than 10% of total daily calories.\n\n### Key Points:\n- **Natural vs. Added Sugars**: Naturally occurring sugars found in fruits and vegetables are generally not a concern, as they come with fiber, vitamins, and minerals. It's the added sugars in processed foods and beverages that are of concern for health.\n  \n- **Moderation**: Consuming sugar in moderation is important. Excessive intake is linked to various health issues like obesity, type 2 diabetes, heart disease, and dental problems.\n\n- **Overall Diet**: Focus on a balanced diet that includes whole foods, and limit processed foods high in added sugars for optimal health.\n\nIt's always a good idea to consult a healthcare provider for personalized dietary recommendations.",
